<DocsLayout
  title="Services"
  description="Configure application services — the containers that make up your app"
  section="Configuration"
>
  <p>
    A <em>service</em> is a Docker container that Shuttle manages as part of your application.
    Each service in <code>shuttle.yml</code> maps to one container (or one set of replicas in
    Swarm mode) running your application code.
  </p>
  <p>
    Services are different from <a href="/docs/configuration/accessories">accessories</a>: services
    run your application image (built from <code>build</code> or pulled from <code>image</code>),
    while accessories run third-party images like Postgres or Redis.
  </p>

  <h2>Minimal configuration</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  web:
    port: 3000</code></pre>
  <p>
    This is the most common configuration. The <code>web</code> service is started using the
    default command from the <code>Dockerfile</code> (<code>CMD</code>) and exposed on port 3000.
    Caddy proxies incoming requests to this port.
  </p>

  <h2>Service fields</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Key</th>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Required</th>
        <th>Default</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>command</code></td>
        <td>string</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td>Dockerfile CMD</td>
        <td>Override the Docker image's default command.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>port</code></td>
        <td>number</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Container port to expose via the proxy. Services without a port are not proxied.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>replicas</code></td>
        <td>number</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td><code>1</code></td>
        <td>Number of container replicas (Swarm strategy only).</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>healthcheck</code></td>
        <td>object</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>HTTP health check configuration. See below.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Health checks</h2>
  <p>
    A health check polls an HTTP endpoint on the container and gates traffic cutover.
    Shuttle will not switch Caddy to the new container until the health check passes.
    If it never passes within <code>deploy.timeout</code> seconds, the deploy is rolled back.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  web:
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up          # HTTP GET path
      interval: 10s      # polling interval
      timeout: 5s        # per-request timeout
      retries: 6         # consecutive failures before giving up</code></pre>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Key</th><th>Type</th><th>Default</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>string</td><td><code>/</code></td><td>HTTP path to poll. Must return 2xx to be considered healthy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>interval</code></td><td>string</td><td><code>10s</code></td><td>Time between health check requests.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>timeout</code></td><td>string</td><td><code>5s</code></td><td>Per-request timeout.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>retries</code></td><td>number</td><td><code>6</code></td><td>Number of consecutive successes required before the container is considered healthy.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Port assignment</h2>
  <p>
    For blue-green deployments, Shuttle assigns host ports automatically so that the blue and
    green containers can run simultaneously on the same server without conflict:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-text">host_port = BASE_PORT + (serviceIndex * 2) + slotOffset

where:
  BASE_PORT   = 10000
  serviceIndex = 0-based index of the service in the services map
  slotOffset   = 0 for blue, 1 for green</code></pre>
  <p>
    For a single <code>web</code> service:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Blue slot: host port <code>10000</code> → container port <code>3000</code></li>
    <li>Green slot: host port <code>10001</code> → container port <code>3000</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For two services (<code>web</code> and <code>api</code>):
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>web blue: <code>10000</code>, web green: <code>10001</code></li>
    <li>api blue: <code>10002</code>, api green: <code>10003</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    You do not need to manage these port assignments yourself — Shuttle handles them automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>Multi-service example</h2>
  <p>
    A typical web application with a background worker and a scheduled task runner:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  web:
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 6

  worker:
    command: node worker.js
    # no port — this service is not proxied
    # no healthcheck — worker is considered healthy if it starts without crashing

  scheduler:
    command: node scheduler.js
    # cron-like scheduler process; also not proxied</code></pre>
  <p>
    All three services share the same Docker image. Shuttle starts each as a separate container
    and manages their lifecycle together. During a blue-green deploy, all three containers are
    rotated atomically.
  </p>

  <h2>Worker services without a port</h2>
  <p>
    Services without a <code>port</code> are started but not added to the Caddy upstream.
    They are useful for background workers, schedulers, and queue consumers that do not
    serve HTTP traffic. Shuttle still manages their lifecycle: they are started with the
    new image after a successful deploy and stopped when the old slots are cleaned up.
  </p>

  <h2>Command override</h2>
  <p>
    Override the Docker image's default <code>CMD</code> for a specific service. This is useful
    when a single image runs multiple roles:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  web:
    port: 8000
    command: gunicorn myapp.wsgi:application --bind 0.0.0.0:8000
  celery:
    command: celery -A myapp worker --loglevel=info
  beat:
    command: celery -A myapp beat --loglevel=info</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
